the Breach of Disclosure -- tCollective Redress and Global Governance (Concluding Remarks) -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a  aWhether with regard to mass torts, civil-rights claims or as a means of private enforcement of antitrust and other regulatory policies: Collective redress of civil claims has been gaining in importance in Europe and worldwide. Long associated with the American model of class actions, an increasing number of EU Member States have made their own attempts at collective redress institutions. At the same time, the amendment of the Brussels I Regulation has shied away from dealing with the cross-border aspects of collective redress. In this book, a worldwide group of distinguished experts in private international law, civil procedure and regulatory law evaluate the problems of cross-border collective redress and provide proposals for a "European way" appropriate for the twenty-first century.This very topical work is, thus, indispensable for practitioners, academics, lobbyists and institutional agents.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aClass actions (Civil procedure)zEuropean Union countries. 0aClass actions (Civil procedure). 0aConflict of lawsxClass actionszEuropean Union countries. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh1 aAthanassiou, Lia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAñoveros Terradas, Beatriz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrozolo, Luca G. Radicati di, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorneloup, Sabine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFentiman, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonzález Beilfuss, Cristina, econtributor.